k<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>myFile.txt.","pos":[3128,3224]},{"content":"You must delete both references to the file in order to delete the file.","pos":[3225,3297]},{"content":"Note","pos":[3301,3305]},{"content":"A hard link can only be created for a file on the same volume.","pos":[3310,3372]},{"content":"If you copy a hard-link migration store to another drive or external device, the files, and not the links, are copied, as in a non-compressed migration-store scenario.","pos":[3373,3540]},{"pos":[3545,3670],"content":"For more information about hard links, please see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hard Links and Junctions<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=132934)</ept>"},{"content":"In most aspects, a hard-link migration store is identical to an uncompressed migration store.","pos":[3672,3765]},{"content":"It is located where specified by the Scanstate command-line tool and you can view the contents of the store by using WindowsÂ® Explorer.","pos":[3766,3901]},{"content":"Once created, it can be deleted or copied to another location without changing user state.","pos":[3902,3992]},{"content":"Restoring a hard-link migration store is similar to restoring any other migration store; however, as with creating the store, the same hard-link functionality is used to keep files in-place.","pos":[3993,4183]},{"content":"As a best practice, we recommend that you delete the hard-link migration store after you confirm that the Loadstate tool has successfully migrated the files.","pos":[4185,4342]},{"content":"Since Loadstate has created new paths to the files on your new installation of a Windows operating system, deleting the hard links in the migration store will only delete one path to the files and will not delete the actual files or the paths to them from your new operating system.","pos":[4343,4625]},{"content":"Important","pos":[4629,4638]},{"content":"Using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>/c<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> option will force the Loadstate tool to continu